  "relevant_summary": "Based on 11 replicated trials of bumblebee nest boxes, nest boxes entirely buried 5-10 cm underground with a 30-80 cm long entrance pipe are generally the most effective design (Action 48). Seven replicated trials in the USA, Canada or the UK testing underground nest boxes found between 6% and 58% occupancy rates (Action 48). In contrast, wooden surface or above-ground nest boxes of the kind currently marketed for wildlife gardening are not the most effective design (Action 48). Eight studies testing wooden surface nest boxes showed varying results: five pre-1978 studies in USA or Canada found 10-40% occupancy, while three post-1989 UK studies found very low occupancy of 0-1.5% (Action 48). Four replicated trials that directly compared wooden surface nest boxes with other types all reported that underground, false underground or aerial boxes are more readily occupied (Action 48). Several different types of nest box have been shown to be acceptable to bumblebees, including wooden or brick and tile boxes at the ground surface, underground tin, wooden or terracotta boxes and boxes attached to trees (Action 48). Two replicated trials specifically testing bumblebee nest boxes found very low uptake of 2% or less (Action 80).",
